--------------------------------------------------------------
DESCRIPTION
--------------------------------------------------------------

A GET request was sent to the /users endpoint and all response headers
were inspected. Five standard HTTP security headers — widely considered
mandatory baseline hygiene for any web-facing API — were entirely absent
from the response.

These headers instruct browsers and HTTP clients how to handle the response
safely, and their absence removes standard mitigations for MIME sniffing,
clickjacking, protocol downgrade, caching of sensitive data, and XSS attacks.

--------------------------------------------------------------
PROOF OF CONCEPT  (Evidence)
--------------------------------------------------------------

REQUEST:
  GET https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users
  Response: 200 OK

FULL RESPONSE HEADER AUDIT:
  +---------------------------------+-------------------+-------------------+
  | Header                          | Expected Value    | Status            |
  +---------------------------------+-------------------+-------------------+
  | X-Content-Type-Options          | nosniff           | MISSING           |
  | X-Frame-Options                 | DENY              | MISSING           |
  | Strict-Transport-Security       | max-age=31536000  | MISSING           |
  | Content-Security-Policy         | default-src 'self'| MISSING           |
  | Cache-Control                   | no-store          | MISSING           |
  +---------------------------------+-------------------+-------------------+

HEADERS ACTUALLY PRESENT IN RESPONSE:
  Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8
  Date: Mon, 27 Apr 2026 04:30:00 GMT
  Transfer-Encoding: chunked
  (no security-related headers)

RESULT: 5 of 5 required security headers absent — MEDIUM FINDING

--------------------------------------------------------------
BUSINESS IMPACT
--------------------------------------------------------------

1. X-Content-Type-Options missing: Browsers may perform MIME-type sniffing
   and execute injected content as a different type than intended, enabling
   content-injection attacks.

2. X-Frame-Options missing: API responses can be embedded in malicious
   iframes, enabling clickjacking attacks that trick users into performing
   unintended account actions (e.g. fund transfers, data deletion).

3. Strict-Transport-Security missing: Browsers may downgrade HTTPS
   connections to HTTP on subsequent visits, allowing a network attacker
   to intercept API traffic and steal session tokens.

4. Cache-Control missing: Browsers and shared proxy servers may cache
   API responses containing user PII, exposing sensitive data to subsequent
   users on shared computers or public Wi-Fi exit nodes.

5. Compliance: SOC 2, ISO 27001, and PCI DSS all explicitly require
   the presence of HTTP security response headers.

--------------------------------------------------------------
REMEDIATION  (Priority: SHORT-TERM — fix within 30 days)
--------------------------------------------------------------

Step 1: Add all five headers at the web server configuration layer.
        This is a single config change — no application code modification.

        Nginx example (add to server {} or location {} block):
        add_header X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff" always;
        add_header X-Frame-Options "DENY" always;
        add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains" always;
        add_header Content-Security-Policy "default-src 'self'" always;
        add_header Cache-Control "no-store, no-cache" always;

Step 2: Validate header presence after deployment:
        Use https://securityheaders.com — enter your API domain
        and confirm all five headers show as green.

Step 3: For APIs serving JSON only, use the restrictive CSP:
        Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'none'
        This is safe and complete for pure API responses.

Step 4: Integrate header validation into CI/CD as a deployment gate.
        Run `curl -I https://your-api.com/health` and assert all
        five headers are present before allowing production deployment.

